All done. Here's the summary:

**Problem:** The `orders` table (500M rows) had only a primary key index on `id`. Every query filtering on `user_id`, `order_date`, `status`, or `amount` was doing a full table scan — scanning half a billion rows each time.

**What I added (all via `CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY` — zero write blocking):**

| Index | Column | Use Case |
|---|---|---|
| `idx_orders_user_id` | `user_id` | Look up a user's orders |
| `idx_orders_order_date` | `order_date` | Date range queries |
| `idx_orders_status` | `status` | Filter by order status |
| `idx_orders_amount` | `amount` | Amount-based queries |

**Safety:** All indexes were built with `CONCURRENTLY`, which uses `ShareUpdateExclusiveLock` — writes (INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE) continued uninterrupted throughout. No lock conflicts recorded. Each took ~3 minutes instead of the 15-minute blocking alternative.

Users should see a dramatic improvement on order-related queries — going from full table scans on 500M rows to fast B-tree index lookups.
